<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;font-size:large;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>IHS News and Views</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <br>
June 11, 2003<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1.‘EC in ER’ Call to Arms</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Rape cannot be prayed out of existence, nor can supernatural forces be relied upon to take care of its consequences. That is why the Institute for Humanist Studies (IHS), joins with New York State Coalition Against Sexual Assault (NYSCASA) and Family Planning Advocates (FPA) to ask the state Senate to pass the “Emergency Contraception in the Emergency Room” bill. <br>
<br>
The bill, S.202, would require all New York hospitals, regardless of religious affiliation, to provide emergency-contraception information and access to rape victims. If used within 72 hours of a sexual assault, emergency contraception can prevent pregnancy in 90 percent of the cases.<br>
<br>
“Too many rape victims have already been faced with violence, have already been victimized and then they go to a hospital to be re-victimized,” said the Hon. Catherine Abate of the New York Health Care Network in a FPA press conference June 4. “Nothing is more unconscionable, inhumane then to tell a rape victim that she cannot receive this kind of help.”<br>
<br>
However, this state’s Catholic Conference says it will not allow its hospitals to deliver emergency-room services it considers immoral, and that includes administering emergency contraceptives.<br>
<br>
Religiously affiliated hospitals are public institutions, receiving government funding to provide secular services. Such hospitals received $40 billion from the government last year. This status makes them subject to legislative regulation. Furthermore, the IHS considers it immoral for religious facilities to stick to church doctrine and deny women, already suffering the trauma of a sexual assault, access to the full range of medical care available. A victim of sexual assault, who may not share the religious convictions of the facility where she is seeking medical attention, should not have the added burden of disinformation and fear of pregnancy placed on her during this traumatic time.<br>
<br>
The New York Assembly approved its version of the bill earlier this year. The Senate version of the bill is stuck in committee. You can help get it out before the session ends on June 19. To send a letter to your senator in support of S.202, visit the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://humaniststudies.org/nylegislation.html?id=1&amp;letter=yes" target="top">IHS Web site</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> or send a letter via e-mail by visiting http://www.senate.state.ny.us/
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>2. ‘EC in ER’ Letters Continue</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
The Institute’s May 20 letter to the editor supporting passage of the “EC in the ER” bill has resulted in a small firestorm of response over the last few weeks.<br>
<br>
Published in the Albany Times Union, the Institute’s letter called for passage of S.202 and outlined the IHS position that religious institutions offering secular services should be held to the same standards and practices as nonreligious institutions. <br>
<br>
So far, the IHS letter has provoked <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.humaniststudies.org/enews/ecletters.html" target="top">seven responses</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. To write your own letter to the editor, send it via e-mail to tuletters@timesunion.com. The TU limits most letters to 250 words.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
