A girl gets raped and beaten, and is taken into the emergency ward.  Since she is unconscious at the time that she is picked up by the ambulance, they rush her to the nearest hospital, which happens to be a religiously affiliated hospital, who condemns the use of contraceptives.  Her religious background is not the same as the religious background of the institution and does permit the use of contraceptives.  Based on her first amendment rights, she should have access to the medication.  Her injuries are quite severe, and she does not regain consciousness until 65 hours after conception.  The medication is usually only reliable up to about 72 hours after conception, thus she has about 7 hours to have the medication administered.  Seven hours may seem like a long time, but after she becomes fully aware of the situation, and the fact that she can't get the medication, there may be 2 or 3 hours left.(Doctors can often take awhile to get around to you)  She no longer has the time to go to a hospital who will give her the required medication, and thus because the hospital enforced their own beliefs upon the victim, she delivers a child that she is not able to properly care for.  The child grows up neglected and abused, and goes out and rapes another poor young girl.  The cycle repeats itself...<br>
